Why `!e.isComposing` alone didn't work (this is the non-obvious part):

On macOS's built-in Japanese IME, when the user presses Enter to confirm
a candidate, `compositionend` fires *before* the Enter keydown, so by
the time `onkeydown` runs, `e.isComposing === false` and `e.keyCode === 13`.
The first pass (just `!e.isComposing`) passed svelte-check and looked
right, but the confirming Enter was still sending messages — verified
live in the Tauri desktop app.

The working pattern needs all three:
  1. `oncompositionstart` → `composing = true`
  2. `oncompositionend` → `setTimeout(() => composing = false, 0)` (NOT
     immediate — the confirming Enter keydown is scheduled right after
     compositionend and must still see the flag as true)
  3. keydown check: `!e.isComposing && !composing && e.keyCode !== 229`

Why defer clearing with setTimeout(0): putting it on the macrotask queue
lets the Enter keydown finish processing before the flag flips. Clearing
synchronously in compositionend would mean keydown sees false and submits.

VariablePopup didn't get the full pattern because it's a child that
receives a pre-fired KeyboardEvent from its parent — no input ownership,
no place to attach composition listeners. It gets the weaker
`!e.isComposing && keyCode !== 229` guard, which handles the
"still-composing" case but not the post-compositionend case. Acceptable
trade-off for a variable-picker popup (accidentally picking a variable
is recoverable).

The bundled Tauri sidecar at crates/xpressclaw-tauri/binaries/xpressclaw-<triple>
is embedded from frontend/build/ at CLI release-build time via rust-embed.
When iterating on frontend fixes for the desktop app, you MUST rebuild
the CLI (./build.sh --skip-test --skip-tauri --skip-docker --skip-check)
and re-copy to binaries/ before launching tauri dev — otherwise tauri's
externalBin copy stays stale and the window loads the old embedded JS.
`cargo tauri dev` also drops the bundled binary at target/debug/xpressclaw,
which is what the desktop app's current_exe-relative sidecar resolver
actually picks up in dev mode.

Inputs NOT touched (VariablePopup aside) that still have only
!e.isComposing: none — every Enter-submit handler in the frontend got at
least the keyCode !== 229 check. Search for `key === 'Enter'` in
frontend/src to confirm coverage if adding new inputs.
